dashboard.definition:
{
	"visualizations": {
		"viz_markdown": {
			"type": "splunk.markdown",
			"options": {
				"markdown": "# Problem description\n\nSome applications, such as [Docker](https://docs.docker.com/config/containers/logging/json-file/), use JSON object wrappers to encode log events. This can be problematic for Splunk which does not natively recognise the JSON loging format. These applications can typically be configured to generate ordinary logs but most frequently they are left on the default setting and the file monitored.\n\n#### Example log line from docker\n\n[Source](https://docs.docker.com/config/containers/logging/json-file/)\n\n    {\"log\":\"Log line is here\\n\",\"stream\":\"stdout\",\"time\":\"2019-01-01T11:11:11.111111111Z\"}\n\n## Existing Solutions\n\nIt is very common for [FluentD](https://docs.fluentd.org/v/0.12/output/splunk)) to be used to read, enrich and convert the JSON log data to a more Splunk friendly format. Alternatively the data can be ingested as a simple `_raw` with JSON encoding which leads to unnecessary passing at search time. Reading JSON log files as `INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS=JSON` does not work as the log string is written to the `TSIDX` as a user defined indexed field. \n\n## Proposed Solution\nWe will use `INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS=JSON`to read the file and then use `INGEST_EVAL` to reassign the `log` field to `_raw` and drop the `time` indexed field. This process removes the JSON wrapper and restores the log file its simplest format ideal for ingestion by Splunk. \n\nIt is important to note that the Splunk to Splunk (s2s) transport protocol sends data as parsed or unparsed. Typically data is send from a universal forwarder as unparsed and it comes parsed when it flows through a heavy forwarder or indexer pipeline. You are able to force the indexer or heavy forwarder to reparse the data by forcing data back into the typing queue.\n\n    [splunktcp]\n    route = [has_key|absent_key:<key>:<queueName>;...]\n    * Settings for the light forwarder.\n    * The receiver sets these parameters automatically -- you do not need to set\n    them yourself.\n    * The property route is composed of rules delimited by ';' (semicolon).\n    * The receiver checks each incoming data payload through the cooked TCP port\n    against the route rules.\n    * If a matching rule is found, the receiver sends the payload to the specified\n    <queueName>.\n    * If no matching rule is found, the receiver sends the payload to the default\n    queue specified by any queue= for this stanza. If no queue= key is set in\n    the stanza or globally, the receiver sends the events to the parsingQueue.\n\n\nWhen structurd parsing (i.e. `INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS`) is enabled on a universal forwarder the default behaviour changes and the universal forwarder produces parsed data for this source. This means that any processing should be done done locally on the universal forwarder by forcing data to processed locally.\n\n    force_local_processing = <boolean>\n    * Forces a universal forwarder to process all data tagged with this sourcetype\n    locally before forwarding it to the indexers.\n    * Data with this sourcetype is processed by the linebreaker,\n    aggerator, and the regexreplacement processors in addition to the existing\n    utf8 processor.\n    * Note that switching this property potentially increases the cpu\n    and memory consumption of the forwarder.\n    * Applicable only on a universal forwarder.\n    * Default: false\n\n### Steps\n\n1. Set props to load data with `INDEXED_EXTRACTIONS=CSV`\n    1. (Optional) Enable `force_local_processing=true` so `INGEST_EVAL` will be evaluted on a universal forwarder\n1. Extract the time from the `time` field\n1. Reassign the `log` field to the `_raw` field\n1. Drop the `log` and `time` fields as they are no longer required\n1. Other fields automatically flow through as indexed fields, for instance in this example is the `stream` field\n"
			}
		},
		"viz_conf_props": {
			"type": "splunk.markdown",
			"options": {
				"markdown": "### props.conf\n\nFrom `default/props.conf` \u2014 verbatim:\n\n```ini\n# Docker JSON log driver embeds the original log line inside a \"log\" field.\n[json_docker]\n# Use the JSON parser to lift every JSON key into an indexed field.\nINDEXED_EXTRACTIONS = JSON\n# Timestamp is the JSON `time` field.\nTIMESTAMP_FIELDS = time\nTIME_FORMAT = %Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S.%QZ\n# INGEST_EVAL moves the embedded log content back into _raw and drops the\n# JSON wrapper fields.\nTRANSFORMS-json_docker = json_docker_reassign_raw_drop_time\nSHOULD_LINEMERGE=false\nLINE_BREAKER=([\\n\\r]+)\n```\n"
			}
		}
	},
	"dataSources": {},
	"defaults": {
		"dataSources": {
			"ds.search": {
				"options": {
					"queryParameters": {
						"latest": "$global_time.latest$",
						"earliest": "$global_time.earliest$"
					}
				}
			},
			"ds.spl2": {
				"options": {
					"queryParameters": {
						"latest": "$global_time.latest$",
						"earliest": "$global_time.earliest$"
					}
				}
			}
		},
		"visualizations": {
			"global": {
				"showProgressBar": true
			}
		}
	},
	"inputs": {},
	"layout": {
		"options": {},
		"globalInputs": [],
		"tabs": {
			"items": [
				{
					"layoutId": "layout_1",
					"label": "New tab"
				}
			]
		},
		"layoutDefinitions": {
			"layout_1": {
				"type": "grid",
				"structure": [
					{
						"item": "viz_markdown",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 0,
							"y": 0,
							"w": 1440,
							"h": 703
						}
					},
					{
						"item": "viz_conf_props",
						"type": "block",
						"position": {
							"x": 0,
							"y": 703,
							"w": 1440,
							"h": 480
						}
					}
				],
				"options": {
					"width": 1440,
					"height": 960
				}
			}
		}
	},
	"description": "",
	"title": "Loading json-docker logs"
}
